\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 There are no sound files \'97 that's the neat part. Every sound is 
\f2\b synthesized live in code
\f0\b0 , the moment it's needed, using the browser's Web Audio API. The entire "sound bank" is about 60 lines of JavaScript inside 
\f3\fs26 index.html
\f0\fs24  (the block beginning at 
\f3\fs26 function _audio()
\f0\fs24  through the 
\f3\fs26 sfx\'85
\f0\fs24  palette): oscillators generate the tones, a generated noise buffer makes the whooshes and stamp, and even the reverb is a synthetic impulse response computed at first use. When a card flips, the whoosh doesn't play from disk \'97 it's 
\f4\i calculated into existence
\f0\i0  right then.\
This is why the audio has zero footprint in the repo, nothing to load or cache, no format/codec issues, and works identically offline and inside the Unreal WebView. It's also why every sound could be tuned by editing numbers \'97 a frequency here, a duration there \'97 rather than re-recording anything. 
\f3\fs26 SOUND_LIBRARY.md
\f0\fs24  documents the recipes.\
If it would be useful, though, I 
\f4\i can
\f0\i0  render the whole palette out as actual 
\f2\b .wav files
\f0\b0  \'97 replicating each synthesis recipe offline and packaging a 
\f3\fs26 sounds/
\f0\fs24  folder with one file per name from the library. Three reasons your team might want that: your sound designer could audition and critique the set outside the game; the Unreal team might want the same sonic identity as native assets in Level 1/3 (so the mini-game and the 3D city share a voice); and it gives you an archive of the current sound design independent of the code. The game itself wouldn't change \'97 it would keep synthesizing live \'97 the files would purely be reference/export artifacts.\
Say the word and I'll render the set.\
