Two technical notes from the included README: a 
\f2\b uniform +12dB audition gain
\f0\b0  is applied so the quiet UI ticks are comfortably auditable \'97 but 
\f4\i relative
\f0\i0  levels between files match the in-game mix exactly, so the hierarchy (ticks whisper, stamp thunks, finales bloom) is preserved for design judgment. And the renderer itself lives in the repo at 
\f3\fs26 tools/render_sounds.py
\f0\fs24  \'97 whenever we tune a sound in the game code, one command regenerates the whole reference set, keeping code and archive in sync.\
For your design work, this gives you three things: an 
\f2\b auditionable palette
\f0\b0  to play through in any audio app and critique sound by sound; a 
\f2\b handoff kit
\f0\b0  for the Unreal team, so Levels 1 and 3 can adopt the same sonic identity as native assets and the trilogy speaks with one voice; and a 
\f2\b versioned archive
\f0\b0  of today's sound design independent of the code. The 
\f3\fs26 sounds-reference/
\f0\fs24  folder and the tool are both in the repo package. Enjoy the listening session \'97 I'd start with the two flips back to back, then the wrong-call thud with its tail.\
